mplied by which `isValid` matches: `uuidv4.isValid` accepts only version 4, `uuidv7.isValid` accepts only version 7."],[260,"Import"],[348,"Import"],[422,"Independent runtimes choose their identity randomly, so uniqueness across them remains probabilistic rather than host-anchored as in Go's `rs/xid` implementation."],[14,"Inspect"],[3,"Install"],[115,"Install"],[300,"Install @uniku/cli when you need an ID in a terminal, migration, or shell pipeline. It shares the library's formats but has its own release lifecycle."],[294,"Install uniku once, then choose the identifier that fits the boundary in front of you: a database index, a public URL, or an API payload. Every generator has its own entry point, so a UUID, ULID, TypeID, Nanoid, CUID v2, KSUID, ObjectID, XID, or TSID only adds the strategy your application imports."],[17,"Installs the current standalone binary without requiring Node.js:"],[211,"Integrations"],[302,"Keep familiar formats while moving to direct, portable imports."],[10,"ksuid"],[153,"KSUID"],[246,"KSUID"],[392,"KSUID"],[394,"KSUID combines a timestamp with a large random payload. Choose it for high-volume distributed systems that need chronological order and a 27-character URL-safe string."],[62,"Length of the ID, 1-256 (default: `21`)"],[72,"Length of the ID, 2-32 (default: `24`)"],[198,"Matches MongoDB's 12-byte ObjectID format."],[201,"Matches rs/xid's compact 12-byte text and binary format."],[301,"Migrate from other libraries"],[331,"Migrate to uniku v1"],[312,"Migration is usually an import change first. Keep the stored identifier format stable, then move generation behind the new direct entry point. Every example below shows the value returned by the uniku generator."],[261,"Minified + gzipped"],[196,"MongoDB `_id` compatibility"],[400,"MongoDB-compatible 12-byte identifiers."],[389,"Most generator modules re-export all four classes, so you rarely need to import from `uniku/errors` directly. Nanoid and CUID v2, which have no binary codec, only re-export `InvalidInputError` and `UniqueIdError`."],[122,"Most generators follow the same pattern: call the generator, keep its primary value, and validate unknown input at the boundary."],[333,"Move CUID v2 to the versioned entry point"],[8,"nanoid"],[149,"Nanoid"],[191,"Nanoid"],[252,"Nanoid"],[395,"Nanoid"],[254,"Nanoid (10 chars)"],[397,"Nanoid is the compact choice for short URLs, invite codes, and session tokens. Its default alphabet is URL-safe; pass a length or options only when the boundary needs a different shape."],[202,"Native `BIGINT` storage"],[109,"No output, exit code only (`0` valid, `2` invalid)"],[90,"Node ID (`0` to `2^node-bits - 1`)"],[195,"Non-sequential, secure identifier."],[341,"Non-sequential, string-native identifiers that resist enumeration."],[255,"npm is 1.1× faster"],[257,"npm is 1.7× faster"],[28,"Number of IDs to generate (default: `1`)"],[11,"objectid"],[157,"ObjectID"],[197,"ObjectID"],[250,"ObjectID"],[399,"ObjectID"],[401,"ObjectID matches MongoDB's native 12-byte representation. Use it when your application stores `_id` values alongside MongoDB clients or needs to preserve that wire format."],[114,"One install, every ID strategy. Import the generator your application needs."],[23,"Option"],[32,"Option"],[41,"Option"],[50,"Option"],[57,"Option"],[67,"Option"],[74,"Option"],[80,"Option"],[85,"Option"],[95,"Option"],[102,"Option"],[30,"Output as a JSON array instead of one ID per line"],[100,"Output as JSON"],[111,"Output as JSON"],[39,"Output in lowercase"],[48,"Output in lowercase"],[226,"Performance and bundle size"],[292,"Pick an ID format for the job, then import only that generator."],[332,"Prepare for the v1 entry-point contract without changing identifier data."],[128,"Primary value"],[187,"Public API resources"],[174,"Public inputs are validated. Explicit random bytes and buffer offsets make tests and boundary integrations deterministic without changing the generator's default monotonic state."],[349,"Purpose"],[412,"