cludes that external dependency's own weight."],[421,"The default identity is random and cached for this runtime. Supplying `machineId` or `processId` changes only that field; calls still use the shared counter unless you also supply `counter`. Supply all four fields for deterministic output."],[337,"The generator behavior is the same. This is an import migration, not a data migration: existing CUID v2 values remain valid."],[20,"The installer resolves the latest CLI release automatically. Set `UNIKU_INSTALL_DIR` to choose a destination:"],[293,"The library contract"],[299,"The library is ESM-only, built on web standards, and tested end to end across Node.js, Bun, Deno, browsers, and Cloudflare Workers. The stability contract defines the entry points, validation boundaries, and runtime support policy that take effect with `uniku@1.0.0`."],[231,"The numbers below come from the repository's own benchmark and bundle-size tooling, including the rows where an npm alternative wins. Benchmarks run in CI on every push to `main` (GitHub Actions, `ubuntu-latest`), so they reflect ordinary Node.js execution rather than a tuned environment."],[346,"The package root is intentionally not exported. Import a generator or metadata module directly:"],[314,"The rest of `uuid`'s API maps onto uniku's per-generator methods, scoped to the version you imported:"],[344,"The stable direct imports exposed by uniku."],[94,"The type is auto-detected unless `--type` is given. For time-ordered IDs (UUID v7, ULID, TypeID, KSUID, ObjectID, XID, TSID), inspect extracts the embedded timestamp. Random-only IDs (UUID v4, CUID v2, Nanoid) report that no decodable metadata is available. Timestamp precision matches each generator: UUID v7, ULID, and TSID are millisecond-precision; KSUID, ObjectID, and XID are second-precision."],[116,"The usual shape"],[216,"These examples are the complete Bun test files from the `uniku` repository. Clone the repository and run `pnpm examples:check` to typecheck and execute all three with the Bun version pinned in `mise.toml`."],[171,"This matters when an ID lives in a binary database column, a compact protocol payload, or a cache key. A UUID, for instance, is 16 bytes instead of its 36-character string form. The helpers also make the string boundary explicit: convert when data leaves your application, preserve bytes where the system already handles bytes."],[233,"This snapshot comes from the rolling `main` baseline updated on July 14, 2026. Treat the ratios as directional: shared-runner noise and dependency updates can move them. The live baseline is the current source of truth."],[375,"Thrown when"],[179,"Time order leaks creation time"],[178,"Time ordering is local"],[123,"Time-ordered formats also expose `timestamp()`. Each generator page lists its complete public API, including options, constants, and overloads."],[393,"Time-ordered identifiers with a 128-bit random payload."],[416,"Time-ordered UUIDs for primary keys, APIs, and event streams."],[186,"Time-ordered values improve index locality."],[403,"Time-sorted 64-bit identifiers for native bigint storage."],[13,"tsid"],[165,"TSID"],[203,"TSID"],[244,"TSID"],[402,"TSID"],[404,"TSID returns a `bigint`, not a string. Use it when a database `BIGINT` primary key is the natural representation and you still need time ordering without a central allocator."],[347,"Two metadata entry points round out the library:"],[55,"Type prefix, e.g. `user` for `user_...` (empty by default)"],[368,"Typed, machine-readable errors for invalid input, malformed strings, and buffer bounds."],[351,"Typed, machine-readable input, parse, and buffer errors."],[7,"typeid"],[141,"TypeID"],[188,"TypeID"],[242,"TypeID"],[405,"TypeID"],[407,"TypeID wraps a UUID v7 suffix in a lowercase prefix such as `user_` or `order_`. It is useful when a public identifier should reveal the kind of resource it identifies."],[6,"ulid"],[137,"ULID"],[236,"ULID"],[408,"ULID"],[410,"ULIDs sort by creation time and stay shorter than a hyphenated UUID. Use them when the value will often appear in URLs, logs, or APIs."],[316,"uniku"],[120,"uniku is ESM-only. Import the exact generator you want rather than a package-root barrel:"],[313,"uniku only generates UUID v4 and v7. There is no uniku equivalent for v1, v3, v5, or v6; keep the `uuid` package for those, or generate them elsewhere and only use uniku for v4 and v7 values."],[335,"uniku v1 keeps its public generator entry points stable and removes one pre-v1 compatibility alias."],[235,"uniku vs npm"],[46,"Unix timestamp in milliseconds, or `now`"],[88,"Unix timestamp in milliseconds, or `now`"],[77,"Unix timestamp in seconds, or `now`"],[83,"Unix timestamp in seconds, or `now`"],[112,"Use `--json` whenever the output feeds another program. The CLI and library publish independently: a library `1.0.0` release does not imply a CLI `1.0.0` release at the same time."],[414,"Use `toBytes()` when the destination stores UUIDs as 16-byte binary values. Use `isValid()` before accepting an unknown UUID v4 string at an application boundary."],[329,"Use `xid.toBytes(id)` and `xid.fromBytes(bytes)` when you store the 12-byte value."],[127,"Usual call"],[5,"uuid"],[129,"UUID v4"],[206,"UUID v4"],[248,"UUID v4"],[411,"UUID v4"],[413,"UUID v4 is the default when compatibility matters more than sort order. It fits databases and APIs that already understand UUID strings."],[133,"UUID v7"],[238,"UUID v7"],[415,"UUID v7"],[406,"UUID v7 identifiers with a readable, domain-specific prefix."],[417,"UUID v7 keeps the UUID shape while embedding a millisecond timestamp. It is a strong default for database primary keys when you want chronological locality without creating a custom ID column."],[185,"UUID v7 or ULID"],[189,"UUID v7 with a readable, domain-specific prefix."],[210,"UUID v7, ULID, KSUID, ObjectID, XID, and TSID embed a creation timestamp in the identifier itself. Anyone who can read the ID can decode when the record was created, not just its order relative to other records. That is a feature for index locality and a leak if the ID is public and the creation time is sensitive, for example a document, invoice, or account that should not reveal how old it is. If the identifier is exposed outside your system and creation time must stay private, use UUID v4, CUID v2, or Nanoid instead: none of them encode a timestamp."],[209,"UUID v7, ULID, ObjectID, XID, and TSID carry time information. uniku keeps the state required for monotonic sequencing inside one JavaScript isolate; it does not coordinate clocks or sequences between processes or machines."],[37,"UUID version: `4` or `7` (default: `4`)"],[170,"UUIDs, ULIDs, TypeIDs, KSUIDs, ObjectIDs, XIDs, and TSIDs have a canonical binary representation. Their `toBytes()` and `fromBytes()` helpers let you store and transport that representation without inventing a second codec."],[15,"Validate"],[193,"Values that should resist enumeration"],[334,"What remains stable"],[227,"Where uniku beats npm alternatives, where it does not, and what each import weighs."],[183,"Why"],[118,"Why byte helpers exist"],[338,"Within `1.x`, uniku will not remove or rename documented entry points, exports, options, methods, or constants. Canonical string formats, byte order, timestamp units, and documented error codes are part of the contract."],[119,"Write into a caller-owned buffer"],[12,"xid"],[161,"XID"],[200,"XID"],[256,"XID"],[418,"XID"],[420,"XID is a 12-byte, lowercase base32hex identifier: a seconds-precision timestamp, a 40-bit per-runtime identity, and a shared 24-bit counter. Use it when you need Go's rs/xid wire format in a synchronous JavaScript runtime."]],"type":"string"},"page_id":{"docs":{"1":10,"2":11,"3":12,"4":13,"5":14,"6":15,"7":16,"8":17,"9":18,"10":19,"11":20,"12":21,"13":22,"14":23,"15":24,"16":25,"17":26,"18":27,"19":28,"20":29,"21":30,"22":31,"23":32,"24":33,"25":34,"26":35,"27":36,"28":37,"29":38,"30":39,"31":40,"32":41,"33":42,"34":43,"35":44,"36":45,"37":46,"38":47,"39"